{
  "texts": [
    "Figure 5 shows how the three metrics of community health change across literature sizes.",
    "Increasing literature size has substantial but mixed effects on the metrics.",
    "When the literature size increases from 200 to 800, the citation-quality correlation decreases by 22.1% in the full model (0.95-0.74, p < 0.001), 21.7% in the null-fixed-reference model (0.92-0.72, p < 0.001), and 22.6% in the null-fixed-threshold model (0.93-0.72, p < 0.001).",
    "Citation churn increases by 26.3% in the full model (22.52-28.43, p < 0.001), 29.3% in the null-fixed-reference model (9.21-11.91, p < 0.001), and 22.8% in the null-fixed-threshold model (10.16-12.48, p < 0.001).",
    "Citation inequality increases by 30.6% in the full model (0.49-0.64, p < 0.001), 22.1% in the null-fixedreference model (0.77-0.94, p < 0.001), and 20.5% in the null-fixed threshold model (0.78-0.94, p < 0.001)."
  ]
}